However, he went on to speculate that the helicopter was moving above the parking lot @   3 to 5 miles per hour. He proceeded by speculating that he was unable to see any (helicopter fog depression) in the fog itself. One might need some type of training to notice " helicopter fog depression" in a fog. So, this really means that he was not exactly sure of the exact location of the helicopter. Finally, he also said that the helicopter that was never in plain sight, managed to make a (left turn) going at 3 to 5 miles an hour. He also speculated that this helicopter crashed 45 seconds later,flying at the speed of 3 to 5 miles an hour,  more than one mile away into the mountains. Also,claiming to hear the sound of ( fiber glass crashing). This is all speculations. It is impossible for any helicopter to travel over one mile, in 45 seconds,moving  @ 3 to 5 miles an hour.  So, he is asking us to believe that he can hear the helicopter crashing one mile away, adjacent to the freeway, making a noise like (fiber glass crashing). This witness is not an expert on say ( helicopter fog depression). This witness was unable to see this helicopter making a left turn either. Because,the  helicopter was never in view. The bottom line is that this witness never saw this helicopter. It is unfair to the public for anyone to pause as an expert on (helicopter fog depression). snippet.textDisplay:
I am trying to figure out how the helocopter was reportedly recorded as crashing at 170-184 mph when it's top speed is 150. Even on a crystal clear day, helocopter pilots won't tax the engines at 100% throttle up(150 MPH), usually flying at 130 MPH.
How did the helocopter which this great detailed witness stated was going only a few miles per hour reach a speed of 170 to 184 miles an hour and impact unless there was something that happened mechanically or otherwise to cause the helicopter to fall from the sky? it seems physically impossible with a top speed of 150 miles per hour that the helicopter would be measured recorded as reaching speeds of about 170 to 184 miles an hour at impact unless it was actually falling from the sky. At any rate with the visibility as bad as it was there's no possible way the pilot would be going full throttle up so the fact that the helicopter was recorded in impact as going 170 to 184 miles per hour makes me suspect some kind of mishap some kind of mechanical problem caused it to free fall from the sky to be going that fast and impact.

SUMMARY OF FINDINGS:

1. The man in this video was pre-screened and selected before the cameras went live. It's important to understand this. A television reporter/anchor person will never go live with a subject that has nothing relevant to say.

2. This man had tons to say. Way too much to say. The man had so much to say and explain that he blew his cover. He is obviously a Critical Incident Scenario Role Player]. That's an official term used by federal/MIL & LEO.

3. The man in the video just happens to be wearing a TWA Airlines baseball cap. That's a prop. It's part of his costume used to psychological condition your subconscious mind to accept him as an expert on aviation flight. Great mission planning work. The masses trust him and swallowed the bait.

4. On this specific day, exactly at the time of the incident, and afterward for this specific television interview, he is on the scene. Perfect timing isn't it?

snippet.textDisplay: What the sound engineer eyewitness said he heard and what actually happened are two very different things. Daelin said he thought the helicopter was going "slow", "3 or 4 mph", and "hovering" . The fact is, the helicopter, according to the radar track on https://www.flightradar24.com/blog/kobe-bryant-believed-dead-in-helicopter-crash/, had a ground speed of at least 125 mph and was accelerating rapidly. The last radar tracks shows the vehicle ground speed around 160 knots -- near 185 mph. Instead of hovering, the helicopter was descending all through its short flight over Las Virgenes -- an accelerating descent that had vertical speed going from 0 to a descent of more than 4000 feet per minute during the last 15 seconds of flight. The large size of the debris field seems to confirm high speed -- not low -- at impact. Both the ground speed and descent rate seem extremely unwise for maneuvering over a narrow mountain valley, and the NTSB will have to determine whether the ground and vertical speeds were unsafe. In fact, high speed can be the CAUSE of spatial disorientation, not the other way around. In any case, the NTSB needs to find out why the pilot turned south over Las Virgenes Road rather than to continue following US 101 for about 24 miles to the Camarillo Airport. The atmosphere and echoes coming off buildings and the ground might have fooled Daelin, who is very earnest. However, a sound engineer knows how ears can be fooled -- in fact, many times, that's his job. By now, I'm sure he knows about these facts.
